name: COL
comment: EB (Mann, priv comm). (THYME) TOI-450, Columba association. Tokovinin already acquired speckle images.  Being pursued by E. Newton & team for RV cluster membership confirmation. Proprietary HARPS specturm in F. Bouchy's hands. SALT/HRS (2), Gemini/IGRINS (2020A)        SALT/HRS, Gemini/IGRINS, THYME Collaboration (Tofflemire). Ziegler did contrast curve. --> IS EB (ANDREW MANN, PRIV COMM.)

name: PscEri
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP0 (V=10.9, Rp=4.0, period=16d, leadership questionable given THYME claim).
comment: TOI-451, Psc-Eri. Zhou/Quinn's CHIRON spectrum shows Li absorption. Ziegler did contrast curve. Has total of THREE PCs on ExoFOPTESS. Spectrum shows vsini=9km/s --> Prot = 5, not 2.5days. WASP shows 4.5day rot period, full amplitude 2%. Verified by SG1. Rodriguez perhaps pursuing mass measurements w/ PFS (but 9km/s means 90m/s jitter expected. Hard to get the masses. If multi, can just validate a la V1298 Tau. T=10, so perhaps worthwhile. DV report indicates multi system seems plausible.). Newton in prep?

name: Pozzo_1,Vela_OB2,cg19velaOB2_pop7,N/A,Pozzo_1,Vela_OB2,cg19velaOB2_pop7,N/A
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2 (V=9.5). CHIRON recon acquired. SpType A or B, mass unlikely, PNEB.
comment: LCOGT(1, non-detection b/c bad epoch; 1 OIBEO 20191216 reduced, but ruined by clouds, 20200213 showed ingress in 25px*0.39as/px=9.75as aperture, quite defocused). "3 GAIA stars within 5" SG1 finds tentative detection in aperture including target and two nearby stars.". SG2 flags as CPC-. Nbhd analysis shows parallax good, pm both viable. Pretty dispersed cluster (few deg) and far from core in ra/dec... and star is on UMS. Needs spectroscopy. Ziegler did contrast -curve. Updated SG1 results say PNEB (possible NEB, but need another epoch to see, however “Next SG1 observation finds event to be more likely on the pair of stars 5" away.”). With infinite time, would get more phot, in focus (i.e., manual tuned LCOGT). However given likelihood of NEB, not scheduling further in 20A.

name: Trumpler_10,N/A,cg19velaOB2_pop2,Trumpler_10,N/A,cg19velaOB2_pop2
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2. (V=9.5). Got CHIRON recon, no more needed.
pending_photometry_observations: PP0, get FOCUSED ip, with deep exposures. After, check for color. Nb. though that this request is impossible with the 1m, we would need 0.4m to do focused observations.
comment: LCOGT (1, non-detection b/c bad epoch, 1 OIBEO 20200101 showing dip on target.). "SG1 clears many stars of NEB, but a handful of potential contami--ts remain. Will try again." SG1 flags as PPC. Parallax good, PM probably within like 1 sigma of cluster PM dispersion. Spatially also medium distance from core (not too far, not too close). Ziegler did contrast curve. Rp=4.7Re. P=1.4d. d=400pc. (Eastman). Rstar=1.7Rsun, Teff~=11000K. Sector8+9 data are available. LC might show extra PCs? CHIRON(1) shows vsini>200km/s, too rapidly rotating to do more spectroscopy with.  If phot confirms on target, can validate from Rp alone (mass measurement unlikely). Age of few tens of Myr, so worthwhile. (Impact parameter b=0.5, from Eastman, and QLP).

name: IC_2602,IC_2602,IC_2602,IC2602
pending_photometry_observations: [todo]PP0 queue i-band for late 20B. -- pre-20201130. Partials?
comment: LCOGT (2, 1 bad epoch, 1 OIB 20200117 that did not show clear transit signal. ). FEROS (4, Rafael Brahm). Has Li. LC shows strong rot signal (2% amplitude). Multisector available (S10+S11, CDIPS, missed b/c TFA over-detrended). SG1 flagged as single transit -- but now it's NOT (P=8days). Despite Gaia & CG18 membership, nbhd analysis shows parallax is nearly 0.25mas larger than typical in cluster -- possibility of foreground star (star isn't particularly bright/blue, no offset argument). PMs are good. Positions are decent. RV is good. P=8d, Rp=8Re (could be higher, like 10Re). vsini=17km/s observed from FEROS. single-lined early-G/late-F type star. Li EW is consistent with a young star (more so than a typical field Teff=6100K G dwarf). Ziegler did contrast curve, compnaion (deltaI=4.5) at ~2.1 arcsec introduces NEB blend scenario. Gaia DR2 also detected the neighbor, and the info of the companion strongly suggests it's bound (same PMs and parallax). There's also a DeltaT=3 star at 5 arcsec, possible blend? (eventually ruled out). CHIRON RV gamma of 16km/s + Li confirms membership (which was good but not definitive from kinematics). CHIRON RV RMS < 1km/s. Go for Veloce, and more phot followup. No more CHIRON needed. Circa 20200401, Phil Evans pinned down a nice followup transit with a 1.5” aperture, boosted to VPC. Excluded more than half the flux of the 2.5” neighbor. 5” N neighbor ruled out, as is the 5” SE neighbor (too faint anyway). The neighbor, 5251470948222139904, has dmag=4.5, so can contribute at most 1.6% flux variations. It has KNOWN PARALLAX, and therefore it is a dwarf star (and probably cluster member, even though not listed), with G=15.06, Bp=14.86, no Rp. Cluster CMD implies Bp-Rp of 2.4, it’s an M dwarf, Teff 4000K or less. Dip depth is 0.4-0.5%. Duration is 1.9 hours (period 8.32 days). Reproducing TESS observations would require a 30% dip on the neighbor. Reproducing P Evans observations (with half the flux of neighbor excluded) would require a 60% dip on neighbor. The angular resolution on his images also seems good enough that a pixel-level analysis will successfully exclude this possibility. The possibility of hierarchical blends is also excluded, based on the sick HRD. I wrote a paper on this object.

name: NGC_2516,NGC_2516,--,NGC_2516,NGC_2516,--
comment: "Crowded field". TIC 372913430. 0.5% dip, P=13.5 days warm jupiter, Teff=9100K. RA/dec in center of cluster, parallax good as well. PMs are 2mas/yr from PM of cluster center. Given the position & parallax, likely not an issue – maybe caused by companion. (RV might clarify). Ziegler got speckle AO, rules out binary companion to ~0.2-0.3 arcsec. Ascribing the offset to companion implies 3km/s orbital velocity, and 60Mjup companion… (Seems likely to be EB in this case!). “QLP reanalysis suggests an NEB (dpeth-aperture correlation)”. SG2 retires as NEB. Worth mentioning in a NGC 2516 homogeneous study, regardless.

name: Platais_5,--,Platais_5,--
comment: SG1 clears field of NEBs, though crowded. vsini=120km/s (CHIRON, Zhou); NRES fast rotator too. Rp=2.0Re, P=0.52d (Eastman). PM of ~10mas/yr in each dirn, d=200pc. NB. Platais 5 moving group is young enough that the KC19 HR diagram shows the PMS for the M dwarfs -- the HRD is awesome. The velocity string is also clear. (CG18 did not report Platais 5, but not surprising b/c of how sparse it is). Nbhd analysis from K13 "members" suggestive but not convincing. FROM K13: ----Plx vs pmdec shows an overdensity, suggesting the group is real. The CMD looks decent. RA/dec not at all convincing. (But note KC19 maybe better for this one...)----- FROM KC19: The neighborhood assessment looks pretty convincing. The RV for this star is where it should be. Two big clumps, PM is right on. Quinn got 2 RVs w/ CHIRON. Ziegler did contrast curve, rules out binary companion to within dM=5 at 1arcsec (~200AU b/c d=200pc), similar down to ~50AU. Given the depth, can probably validate. Need EM1 TESS light curve though.

name: AB_Dor,--,AB_Dor,--
pending_spectroscopic_observations: [todo]SP1 (V=7.3), need 1 CHIRON recon spectrum for stellar params and RV for membership.
comment: "Period is double or four times larger; T0=1481". P~40day. TIC 130415266. Two transits viewed... ! Teff~9600K, T=7.6. Tricky to schedule (for transit followup). HD 52470. Nothing on the HARPS archive. An RV to place it in the strong AB Dor RV stream (or not) would be helpful. In v_l vs longitude (mw2d plot), clearly apparent stream. In the nbhd plots, it's not obvious (but maybe this is a projection problem?) Ziegler did contrast curve. Ephemeris too imprecise for phot followup, uncertainty is 0.5 days. Need TESS EM1 data.

name: Platais_5,--,Platais_5,--
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2, though SQ 1 CHIRON pending. RV might confirm membership, but it’s a A1-IV subgiant. No chance at mass.
pending_photometry_observations: PP2. Need with a <1m telescope (so LCOGT is out), and 2mmag is hard. No good comparison stars.
comment: LCOGT (1, 20191224. 10 mmag precision, no chance for a 3 mmag transit. Not enough comparison stars – was experimental at 2 sec exposure. Result of experiment was: for LCO 1m, bright limit is like V=8.5). "Might be diluted; SG1 to check". From K13 members, not at all convincing. From KC19 members, PM and parallax plausible for it being a member of the stream. NEED AN RV TO CHECK. And spectra to determine youth. NB. independently found this one from CDIPS in Sector 6 -- threw it out b/c was "just ZariUMS PC". But the dips look weirdly close to being in phase w/ some kind of stellar pulsation mode (only every ~4 or 6 oscillations?!). Ziegler got speckle AO, shows binary companion at 2.11arcsec, deltaI=1.3mag. Note TOI 1014 == TIC 96246348 on exoFOP-TESS but this is wrong, it’s TIC 772008799. Note also TOI 1014 == CCDM J06542-3413AB, a known binary (spectroscopic? How?). Primary is a subgiant, SpType A1IV. From TIC8 it seems there are at least 3 relevant stars in the TESS aperture. However one might be double-counted, in which case it’s just the AB binary.

name: kc19group_237,--,kc19group_237,--
comment: LCOGT (1, no detection, but consistent w/ shallow depth). "need SG1 to check 400595381; likely BEB". Group is somewhat weak. A bit too old for PMS to be super-convincing (but maybe other indicators possible). Star membership in group from nbhd plot looks pretty good. (Though the group membership is not much stronger). Not convincing enough to lead.

name: kc19group_64
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP0. SQ 2 CHIRON pending. Need 1 CHIRON recon spectrum. Should see strong Li. Then need 3 RVs to assess mass measurement prospects (Rp=2.5Re, spot amplitude could be larger than planet signal). Validation paper is worthwhile if mass measurement will require many seasons. March thru April 2021 are the time to hit it hard with PFS, if possible.
pending_photometry_observations: [todo]PP1. Get 1 ip-band transit. Awesome target, but transits are quite shallow. One LCOGT ip-band, just to play it safe that it’s not EB. -- available <20201130.
comment: LCOGT (20200209, BEO, too high scatter to detect 500ppm transit). "bright potential L1 candidate". QLP shows ~0.5-1% strong rotational variability (as-in, strong young star). The PMS of the group looks good. Star has plx of ~12.5mas, compared to group mean of ~9.8 pm 1mas. Nbhd analysis shows the group is definitely real. Like it's a freakin whopper. Young enough that spectra (Li, Halpha,..) will clarify youth. Worth pursuing. Mann weakly suggests a secondary eclipse, but now retracts. Manual inspection of QLP LC does show some additional dips, but not obviously secondary eclipses. Not S11+S12 TESS data are available. Too low SNR in S11 CDIPS LC (b/c small and P=9days). Johanna Teske interested; Armstrong and Gandolfi (HARPS) have acquired 7 RVs. Talk with Teske about getting the mass. Note Prot of 6.5d is long given the supposed age of 50 Myr and Teff 5880. Would imply gyro age of 500 Myr. Why is it spinning slowly? The S11 CDIPS report also indicates that the star just hit ZAMS. Consistent with age of 40-50 Myr given Teff.

pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP1, low priority for 1 PFS recon spectrum (look for Halpha). No CHIRON necessary, or possible. TripleSpec proposal possible.
comment: LCOGT(1 IBEO ambiguous; 1 OIBEO i-band good). Many HATS(good). Possible PMS dwarf with close-in giant planet (else EB). ~4% amplitude spot signal. T~=15 and red, so maybe best for a NIR spectrograph?. From LCO2m, have Rp/Rstar=0.24894. Plausible Rp, but the duration is a tad long (implies too low density). My hesitation about this object is that it's faint (T=15, V=17), and that the case for youth isn't amazing. We need AO images to argue against a triple-star system explanation, I think. Maybe Speckle-AO with Zorro on Gemini could do it, but I doubt smaller telescopes could.  I think we would also need to see Halpha emission in a recon spectrum to believe more strongly in the case for youth.  Try for gp band, get 1 recon spectrum w/ PFS (if 30 minutes possible… 1 hour a bit long).

name: NGC_2323
comment: KeplerCam photometry (Allyson Bieryla) shows it's a NEB. Was labelled Giant PC in M50, ~100Myr star with rotational variability. CHIRON (2, Zhou), showed star has double-peaked CCF, large RV variation. RV=24km/s and RV=128 km/s measured. Livingston got a contrast curve too.

pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP1, low priority for 2-3 PFS spectra, else try for TripleSpec (4.1, on the SOAR).
pending_photometry_observations: [todo]PP1. Get zs, then gp band transits. NB might need to update ephemeris based on Bieryla’s observation.
comment: SG1 (Allyson Bieryla, OIBEO 20200112 in ip and confirmed a 26 minute early ~ 45 ppt event in an uncontaminated 3.4" target aperture with FWHM=2.1".) Possible HJ around PMS star. Main worry is stellar-mass EB (and rotation period seems to be near the orbital period). Tdur is 1.9hour, gives correct stellar density. Depth is good.

name: NGC_2516,NGC_2516,NGC2516,NGC_2516
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2, was SP0 before Chiron recon showed SB2 and RV variable.
comment: Retiring as SB2 in NGC 2516, presumably P=12d signal is F+M binary. CHIRON(4). 2 CHIRON epochs show clear SB2 signatures. LCOGT(2, 1 BEO i' good, 1 OIBE in g' with depth comparable to i'). 2 SG1 (Phil Evans, IBE, successful, Kevin Collins LCO 0.4m, total).  P~12 day WJ, NGC 2516. Multiple sector data available (S7,S8,S10)→ would benefit from multi-sector analysis. Gaia-DR2 RV in tension with Soubiran cluster RV, but at low significance -- higher precision RV requested. Otherwise nbhd analysis is good (plx, proper motion, positions all fine).  Ziegler got speckle AO, shows faint double-dot to NE/SW of the ACF at sep 1arcsec -- but Ziegler says is spurious (would be deltamag 4.). d=400pc.  Rstar=1.35, Teff=6150K (TICv8). SQ+GZ from CHIRON found T0308538095, 2019-12-17T06-44-23.0 2458834.79415 RV 18.833 0.034 Teff 6098 logg 4.36 feh 0.04 vsini 13.0. Note the vsini is an upper limit. This argues that the Gaia RV measurement was spurious. Whopping Li, EW=120mA (GZ, 20200122). Given this Teff, and 300Myr, one would expect Prot~4 days. CDIPS LCs have heavy systematics, no obvious Prot. Eleanor LCs hint at 6-7day rotation? Again though, not obvious.

name: Alessi_3,Alessi_3,--,Alessi_3,Alessi_3,--
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP0. (V=10.7). Decent case for a few more 20B observatoins, to clarify the linear trend. Predicted K_planet=15-30m/s, P_orb=1.1d, K_spot=100m/s, P_rot=5d.
comment: Priority for RVs. Cand super neptune. LCOGT(2 ip, 2gp, both OIBEO and good), 1 CHAT (i-band), OIBE/IBEO. All reduced transits are good.  CHIRON(1 recon, GZ email 20191226 2019-12-18T05-41-37.9 2458835.74473 RV -1.586 0.202 Teff 6555 logg 4.09 feh -0.09 vsini 27.2). Gaia DR2 RV good enough to confirm cluster membership. But cluster membership and signal look v good -- this one is worth the effort! NB. sector 8 data are available. Nbhd reanalysis also v good. RVs solid enough. d=294pc. Rstar=1.5, Teff=6750K (lower from CHIRON Teff). Ziegler got speckle AO, rules out binary companion to ~0.2-0.3 arcsec. (Weakly detected) Prot=5d from CDIPS LC, amplitude 0.4%. 7 PFS RVs over 7 nights show linear trend of amplitude 500m/s. 1. There is a dT=4.7 star in the aperture, TIC767810561 = gaia 5510676828723794176. No TIC Rstar, but d=1.35kpc, vs 0.3kpc target. Bp-Rp=0.84. E(B-V) of 0.095. Gaia apsis quotes Teff 5200K. TIC8 Fig8 spline would give 5600K if dwarf.  RV RMS < 1km/s over 14 CHIRON RVs. 7 PFS RVs taken over 7 nights showed a linear trend (with hint of a turnover) with peak-to-peak amplitude 450m/s.  Doesn't obviously phase up with either the expected ~2.5 day rotation period (which is weak from photometry, but vsini strongly indicates it).  Also does not phase up with transit ephemeris, but this was expected.  This object needs a blend analysis for validation -- there is sufficient photometry now to do it (perhaps with one extra LCO g band light-curve to improve the SNR of chromaticity analysis). No further CHIRON observations necessary. PFS if possible (but them expensive). What about Li? Teff 6700 vs 6500 makes a difference... near Boesgaard gap. The spectra do not show Li, but Teff exactly in Boesgaard gap is likely. Note: boosted to be a TOI post-CDIPS. QLP report has impact parameter grazing (b=0.97-1.04), while CDIPS report is b=0.5+/-0.5, so not helpful. On 20201026 we attempted Veloce RM, but had 3 arcsec seeing, so probably not helpful (and Tinney cannot reduce).

name: Vela_OB2,N/A,cg19velaOB2_pop7,Vela_OB2,N/A,cg19velaOB2_pop7
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP1, would be nice to have PFS recon spectrum (desparately, for Rstar and Rp measurement). If good, 7 RVs with PFS could show planetary. Another possible triplespec proposal object. Instead of PFS though (b/c only 10 hrs), go for a 1800 sec CHIRON exposure. [And ideally, have other M dwarf references to compare with]
pending_photometry_observations: Wait until get recon spectrum before g’ or b’.
comment: CHAT (1, IBE). LCOGT (2, BEO, 2 OIBEO iband good). SG1 (Don Radford) 1 OIBEO (iband). V-shaped. Noisy star, 3% dip, PMS M dwarf. TESS data has at least s7+s9. Initially was just Zari+18 PMS, sector 9 boosted to CG19 VelaOB2 + Kounkel19 VelaOB2. CDIPS LCs exist for S7,S8,S9. 20200112: some b or g’-band totals might be nice, otherwise no more photometry needed. Need recon spectrum to determine Rstar better (or else use other method?), and thereby determine if possible planet, or not! (Rp is large). Note E(Bp-Rp)=1.37. 7 RVs could show planetary mass (e.g., HATS-71). TripleSpec4.1 recon spectrrum would be nice.

name: NGC 2546
comment: 20191209: LGB retiring due to unconvincing neighborhood, + weakly suspect depth increase in new S8 data.  Suspect occ depth. Candidate HJ in NGC 2546 (~150 Myr).  TESS S7+S8 available. Astrometric excess indicates likely presence of wide binary companion. RVs to rule out stellar EB needed! Cluster membership looks passable (it's Dias). Nbhd analysis indicates target is maybe 2 sigma away from expected cluster PM dispersion. It is also weakly in the foreground (maybe 1.5-2 sigma). It would be on the periphery of the cluster -- the neighborhood is not convincing.  If it's 150 Myr, where is the rotation signal?  Needs RVs to check for Li.  Worth continuing observations, but difficult to confirm. Teff~=6000K from Gaia Bp-Rp color + TICv8 spline relation, and is flagged as dwarf (TICv8 did not report stellar params, probably b/c of ~1 arcsec companion, deltaMag=2 Gaia DR2 5541111035708733056).

name: Collinder_135,cg19velaOB2_pop4,N/A,Collinder_135,cg19velaOB2_pop4,N/A
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2, Not a planet (young M dwarf secondary). Propose for TripleSpec (4.1, on the SOAR), under the science case of young M dwarf stellar modeling, rather than planets.
comment: LCOGT (1 OIBEO 20200114 showed on target) M-dwarf + HJ/BD/M dwarf. 40 Myr old, Gaia membership is strong. 2.5Rjup radius is standard (see Burrows+2001 cooling track). TESS photometry shows rstar rotation is decoupled from orbital period. Need mass measurement to characterize system -- worth spending some time on. Nbhd analysis shows RA/dec a few deg from Collinder135 center. RV not available. PM good. Plx good. CMD good (pre-MS). Ground based phot implies it’s like M3+M6 dwarf. Transit too deep (Rp~=39Re), even given the age. The age and radius imply it's a low-mass stellar companion, with Mstar~0.2Msun if Burrows' models are to be believed.

name: NGC_2527,NGC_2527
comment: MIT QLP report shows stronger odd even difference (7sigma) than CDIPS. EB!  Need blend analysis. Priority for RVs. LCOGT(4 useable from  20191215 & 20191217 & 20191224 & 20191229-- consistent, with shallow signals, but not particularly helpful b/c 0.2% dip). Possible super-Neptune, P=1.1 d orbit. CDIPS report centroid analysis not great b/c of crowdedness ...LCO  ground-based photometry (0.2% dip) did help rule out <40” NEB blends though. Nbhd analysis shows in RA/dec it's relatively far from cluster core (2-3 sigma). Plx, PM look great. CMD shows it's a little bit (1-2 sigma) faint. RA/dec space looks like ~2-3 sigma away from cluster center. CG18 Pmemb=90%. CHIRON(1 recon spectrum in fiber mode) shows star RV is consistent with Gaia cluster RV. Li is strong (as expected for Teff=6270K). 2019-11-26, RV 38.348 0.039 Teff 6236 logg 4.32 feh 0.17 vsini 12.0. Shows a "nice broad Li line".  vsini of 12km/s for a Teff=6270K star with Rstar between 1.14Rsun (TIC8) and ~1.3Rsun (Mamajek)implies Prot of ~4.5-5 days, consistent w/ Curtis’ gyro sequences of ~600Myr-1Gyr, and inconsistent with the Prot=10days seen in the field.  MIT QLP report shows stronger odd even difference (7sigma) than CDIPS. EB!

name: Haffner_13
comment: LCOGT(2, egresses). HATS (many G602/3, showed event seems to be off-target). Cand HJ around ~30 Myr star, strong rot variability.  Membership seems pretty good (CG18), but RV to verify couldn't hurt. Centriod looks good, but medium-crowded -- ground-based transit followup also needed. Nbhd analysis shows PMs maybe 1 sigma off. Plx good, position fine, CMD good.

name: ASCC_39
comment: 20191209: LGB retiring due to unconvincing existence of cluster (as visible in neighborhood plots). Cand HJ about K dwarf in ASCC 39. CG18 didnt recover this cluster (raises doubts about existence). Nor did Conrad+17. Cluster would need to be better characterized for strong claims to proceed. Nbhd analysis suggests cluster is maybe coherent in PM and parallax space... but even if it is, the star's membership in the cluster is tenuous. Can follow-up, would be hard to publish.

name: NGC_2421
comment: Phil Evans ruled out 21 ppt event on target, confirmed 200 ppt NEB on neighbor 7" East (w/ a 3" aperture). --> It's a NEB. LCOGT(2, 1 ambig, other ?).  Cand ultra-HJ on 16hr orbit around evolving(?) star in a ~40 Myr old cluster, at ~2kpc. Either (a) stellar EB, given dip size, or (b) inflated/still contracting giant planet / BD. Probably (a), but this one is worth checking. Nbhd analysis shows PMs good, parallax good, CMD is slightly turning off, position fine (maybe 1 sigma from center).

name: IC_2602,--,IC_2602,--
comment: LCOGT(3, 20200131 and 20200204 ip, 20200208 gp). ip vs gp shows strong chromaticity. Initially possible HJ in IC2602; but it's an EB. 2x TLS period.

pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2 (V=13). SB2. Triple-lined recon spectrum from CHIRON. Unlikely to ever yield mass without very dedicated campaign.
comment: LGB retiring 20200308 as on-target EB (PMS K dwarf) due to odd-even persistence after better detrending. Odd-even affected by spot detrending. Cand HJ, PMS K dwarf (Zari+18). Multisector (S9-S11). Nice Prot~=4.0days, ~3% amplitude. Roughly 2x planet period. That’s sub-Pleiades gyro age. 1 transit window obsd by MEarth South (J Irwin) out of window because of bad ephemeris. 1 by Don Radford (Briarfield0.36m). Howell found, in March, no Zorro binary companions.

name: IC_2602,IC_2602,IC2602
comment: 20200119: LGB retiring as PC because extra manual detrending showed its a Mdwarf persistent dipper (shape not at all planetary). Cand super-Neptune; IC2602 (30Myr; CG18). PMS M dwarf. Faint.

name: kc19group_1172
comment: Cand HJ; Theia 1172 (KC19). Cluster existence very questionable.

name: kc19group_1141
comment: NEB (Phil Collins, 2020.03.09, in Ic). This is a bright field star, TIC8 Teff=8500K. CHIRON recon claims Teff=6000K. Retiring from further CDIPS followup, but worth DT verification (P=5.5d, V=10.5).  2020-02-04T08-55-03.8 2458883.8790700003 RV -1.798 0.573 Teff 5940 logg 2.99 feh -0.16 vsini 48.2. Cand WJ, Theia 1141 (KC19). Group existence is weak. (Possibly T=10.5 field star). Hot and bright enough to enable doppler tomography, so worth pursuing regardless. Boosted to TOI postCDIPS.

name: kc19group_908
comment: Cand HJ, Theia 908 (500Myr; KC19). Crowded+faint; neighbor spot signal.

name: NGC_3114
comment: LCOGT(1, 20200203, showed is NEB). Cand HJ; NGC 3114 (300Myr; CG18). Check for NEB.

name: NGC_3114
comment: LCOGT(2, 20200116 OIBEOi-band, showed most likely on-target. 20200204 i-band OIBE showed dip, but 30 nbhrs within 2’ show similar variability. 20200208 and 20200212 gp showed maybe same depth, but still could be NEB.). Near TOI 684 (but different), very hot star. HJ, NGC 3114 (~150Myr, CG18). Multisector. CHIRON(1) yields vsini~=50km/s, no further spec FU needed unless we decide this is worth a shot for DT. But with Bp =12.6, perhaps a bit faint for it.  CHIRON result was 2020-02-08 2458887.84865 RV -0.629 0.911 Teff 7116 logg 3.93 feh 0.24 vsini 48.0. Maybe if more phot FU shows no chromaticity? UT2020.05.14 Hazelwood 32cm (ChrisS) saw 7ppt transit i-band on time, also blended. Karen writes: quotethe apparent egress in the target star light curve is nearly perfectly correlated with FWHM, and detrending using even the short segment that would be out of eclipse, virtually removes the event. Using the same technique with T2, a ~20-25 ppt V-shaped event is seen the neighbor in both ip and gp. TIC8 gives R*=2.1 for the neighbor with no uncertainty. If that is close, then the companion has a radius >32 Re. It would be even deeper because there's still a decent amount of blending in T2 from T1. I'll retire as an NEBquote.

name: NGC2516,NGC_2516,NGC_2516,--,NGC2516,NGC_2516,NGC_2516,--
comment: TOI 681 in NGC 2516 (broad catalog agreement). SG2 lists as Chile-MPIA (4 Coralie, 4 FEROS, looks like a 70 MJ BD). The period is 15 days. At 300 Myr, valuable benchmark! Any NGC 2516 analysis should mention. Rafael Brahm & the Chile-MPIA team are following -- no further RVs needed. It’s ready for writing up (maybe with a few more RVs)

name: kc19group_163
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2 (V=12.4, deep, shows RV variations indicative of SB1 binary).
comment: 20200226, LGB retiring as EB due to large RV variations (24km/s) indicative of a binary anti-phased with the transit ephemeris (CHIRON-Zhou, 2). LCOGT (1, 20200127, well out of transit b/c of imprecise ephemeris. Try again w/ updateephem. 20200214 ip, 20200224 gp combined do not show chromaticity. Phil Evans 20200220 in Rc 45-50ppt.). Cand HJ, Theia 163 member (60 Myr; KC19). Deep transit. Multisector. Prot ~ 1.5 days, compared to ~1.4 for orbital period. But definitely different. Rot amplitude of 7-8%. Good group for Jason and Luke to work on, but stars do seem very coeval vs the nbhd, strongly suggesting group is real. Careful inspection of CDIPS raw LCs shows secondary eclipse, though not necessarily game-ending. Howell found (Mar 2020) no Zorro companions.

name: kc19group_1242
comment: Cand HJ, Theia 1242. Tdur long + maybe TTV?. Cluster maybe nonexistent.

name: Ruprecht_82
comment: 20200118, LGB retiring as EB. Cand HJ (maybe EB). Ruprecht 82 (230Myr; CG18, d=2kpc). Prop motion weakly suspicious. Even if it is 230Myr old, Rp of >3Rjup is highly questionable.

name: kc19group_1242
comment: Cand HJ, Theia 1242. Cluster maybe nonexistent. Hot star.

name: NGC_2925,NGC_2925
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2, it's double-lined, and so probably an EB.
comment: Retired 20200210 as double-lined EB. Cand HJ, NGC 2925 (100Myr; CG18; KC19). Photometric binary likely (wouldnt be subgiant because its before turnoff). Multisector. pmDEC is off, by 0.5 mas/yr. This could be done with a projected onsky orbital velocity of 1.8km/s, which equating to the semiamplitude would give msini of 15Mjup. CDIPS LC has hints of phase modulation in S9 and S10. Teff=7000K, so “precise” mass measurement not a question. But we only need 100m/s precision. 1 CHIRON recon spectrum shows double lined; it's probably an EB.

name: IC_2391,IC2391,IC_2391
pending_photometry_observations: PP1. Get ip, zs. Maybe gp last, but is M dwarf. Check w Joel about reduction status here… Note: none visible pre 20201130
comment: Cand super-Neptune, IC2391 (~80Myr; CG18). PMS M dwarf; faint. Tdur is long (like 2x too long given supposed host star). Schedule 2m ip followup. Unlikely to be persistent dipper, might just be long and off-target. 20200415 Don Radford observed a transit w 0.36m, but too low SNR to confirm/refute. Might as well try 2m (Did try. Result [pending].) 20201104, TRAPPIST-South 60cm in z-band observed got a nice transit; K Collins boosted to VPC.

name: cg19velaOB2_pop2
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2, recon spectrum showed composite, likely SB2.
comment: Retiring as SB2, b/c CHIRON is showing composite spectrum between two rapidly rotating stars. Depth is suspicious too. Cand WJ, Vela OB2 pop2 (<50Myr CG19). If its so young, wouldn’t the star be more active?

name: cg19velaOB2_pop4
comment: Retired 20200204 as NEB/possible field HJ. Cand HJ, Vela OB2 pop4 (20Myr CG19). LCOGT(1, 20200202, showed it’s not on target. There is a flat-bottomed transit on TIC260118987, a 10” neighbor, = Gaia 5329853517263007360. However this neigbhor which likely hosts the dip seems to be somewhat evolved, and is not on the target list. Phil Evans saw the same, off-target, roughly simultaneously). Centroid unclear. If it’s really that young, it should show spots. Likely spurious membership? It’s in the dispersed portion of NGC2541B/pop4. Check for Li.

name: NGC_3532,NGC 3532,NGC3532,NGC_3532,NGC_3532,--,NGC_3532,NGC 3532,NGC3532,NGC_3532,NGC_3532,--
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2 (was SP0 before recon showed EB).
comment: LCOGT(1, OIBE, 20200211, nice on-target ingress, confirm 7 day, not 14!). Nice WJ, NGC 3532 (300Myr;many authors). P=7d or P=14d from TESS. 4 transits over S10&S11. Good DT target. Evans observed odd ingress in Rc 20200225, confirmed on-target and 7 day. Retiring as P=7day EB in NGC 3532. Presumably A+M dwarf. 3 CHIRON spectra showed extremely narrow lines, indicative of tidal synchronization by a high mass companion. Also showed RV variability over these 3 epochs at 20km/s. Howell found (Mar 2020) no Zorro companions.

name: NGC_3532,NGC3532,NGC_3532
comment: Cand super-Neptune; NGC 3532; initially flagged as “maybe false alarm” but it seems clearly in LC. Need LC with ~mmag precision (depth 2 mmag). Reasonably crowded – might be on a neighbor star. CHIRON recon gives broad lines, 2020-02-03T08-00-08.2 2458882.8414 RV 7.053 0.062 Teff 6254 logg 4.22 feh 0.03 vsini 20.6. RV agrees with Gaia dn cluster mean. So does vsini. Need the phot followup. LCOGT 20200215 OIBEO ip challenging reduction, but maybe saw egress.  CHIRON(2) shows RVs show 2km/s variations in phase with the transit ephemeris. Perhaps misclassified, and it's a BD (or blended EB) and not a 6Re planet.  LGB will schedule 2 additional CHIRON slicer/fiber observations, as appropriate. 3 CHIRON RVs show a 2km/s variation, perhas indicating a BD or stellar companion. Closer inspection of vetting report shows it’s probably offtarget, leading to demotion. For some reason, was boosted to TOI post-CDIPS. (And after my demotion). Howell found (Mar 2020) no Zorro companions.

name: IC_2602
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2. Put it on the TripleSpec proposal.
comment: Cand super-Neptune; IC2602 (30Myr; KC19). PMS M dwarf. Faint. Tdur is long (2.4hr vs 0.8hr predicted). Suspect it’s another Mdwarf persistent dipper. The shape is a bit weird. d=130pc, they don’t get much better! But Rp=15.6, T=15.7. W-shaped transit. Likely should wait for EM1 data on this one.

pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2. It’s faint. Put it on TripleSpec proposal.
comment: Cand HJ; PMS M dwraf (Zari+18). No stellar rotn (worrying). Check spectra for activity.

name: kc19group_988
comment: Cand 1.1d HJ, Theia 988 (~500Myr; KC19). Short period rotn(?) signal too. Multisector. Porb=1.094968, Prot=0.264554. No harmonic. “Rotation” looks more like contact EB though. Strongly suspect group is not real – the HR diagram is garbage.

name: NGC_2516
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP0. Good for 20B more PFS shots, to pin down planet mass and the linear trend.  Predicted K_planet=204m/s, P_orb=0.95d, K_spot=135m/s, P_rot=6d.
comment: LCOGT (3, OIBEO, consistent w TESS and on-target.  20200121, 20200129, 20200131 LCO show same. 20200214 in rc by Phil Evans. 20200214 gp shows no chromaticity. 20200421 zs acquired, and looks good.). Cand HJ, NGC 2516 (300Myr; KC19). Bright in cluster HR diagram, need AO imaging to constrain possible companions. At Teff=5700K, shouldnt it show rotation? Yes, and it does, at Prot~6 or 7 days from CDIPS LC. Maybe ~1.5% amplitude. This is exactly what the Curtis+19 gyro relations would predict. Also, Gaia plx, PMs look great, it’s the ra/dec that probably led it to not being a CG18 member. NB. DR2 RV is perfectly with cluster as well (RV=27.77km/s). vsini=7.7 pm 0.5 km/s from GZ’s LSD profile, in agreement with Prot. Nice! Note: boosted to TOI postCDIPS. QLP report shows impact parameter 0.80 and 0.92, i.e. it is not grazing). Howell found, in March 2020, no Zorro binary companions.

name: NGC_2547
comment: Retiring as SB2 from 2 CHIRON epochs. Cand HJ, NGC 2547 (30Myr; KC19). LCOGT (2, 20200116 shows on-target and consistent, 20200203, 20200212 showed same depth, but shape is more like a blended EB than a planet). SG1 (El Sauce, Phil Evans) verifies as VPC, Phil Evans observed a full on 20200203 in Ic and confirmed a 26 ppt V-shaped event in a 5.1" target aperture, which is not contaminated with a star bright enough to cause the event in the target aperture. 1 extra SG1 from Chris S Hazelwood, ingress. From TESS, maybe odd-even (but seems more like LC artifact); check star for activity.There’s a T=9 neighbor 30 arcsec away, but seems unlikely to be on it (ground-based followup confirmed). Teff=6800K, so a bit odd the star isn’t more active. Need spectra to check for Li and mass suitability. 20200127 CHIRON recon shows double-lined binary, with no lithium.  2020-01-27T05-49-00.7 2458875.75427 RV 53.676 0.141 Teff 6247 logg 4.1 feh -0.3 vsini 13.3. It’s also a photometric binary from HR diagram.

name: BH_34
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP0 (V=14.2). Worth checking with e.g., CHIRON or even PFS.
comment: Cand WJ, BH 34 (70Myr; KC19). Quite deep. (Maybe EB). LCOGT (1, 20200210, ip, on-target and good; ditto Phil Evans 20200210 ip). 1 CHIRON spectrum (which had a wonky Mgb order) shows 2020-02-11T04-24-38.7 2458890.71953 RV 5.998 0.063 Teff 5873 logg 4.4 feh 0.14 vsini 12.9.  If Teff is really this low, means could be planetary. The "cluster" in KC19 is apparently 3 wonky clumps. The dips, at 5%, are also very deep, suggsting an EB. Weak Li in the recon spectrum. The 6km/s RV from the CHIRON spectrum is weakly inconsistent with the KC19 "member" RVs. Vsini implies 3.6d rot period, roughly consistent with Pleiades at Teff of 5900K. The photometric rotation period has small amplitude and is hard to detect, maybe 0.2%? NB also the Gaia HRD favors the Teff 5900K solution over the massive star 7600K solution given by the TIC. The TIC solution is probably a reddening problem. Really would like a better recon spectrm to be sure about youth here.

name: N/A,cg19velaOB2_pop2
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2. (V=15. K=12. Teff=4700K K dwarf). Good for TripleSpec proposal, but EB.
comment: 20200220 LGB ruling as EB (on target) due to gp vs ip chromaticity. 20200209 Phil Evans confirmed on target ip. 20200219 LCO gp showed strong chromaticity. Probably EB, else HJ in Vela OB2 pop2 (<50Myr, CG19). S7 and S8 available.

name: N/A,cg19velaOB2_pop7
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2, was SP0. Hold for further spec (have 1 Veloce, 1 CHIRON).Predicted K_planet=110m/s, P_orb=3.2d, K_spot?=40m/s, P_rot?=3d.
comment: Retiring as SB2 from 2 CHIRON epochs. LCOGT Phot FU showed this target was on the neighor (5 arcsec away), but a 5" neighbor that is SB2 is nonetheless worrying enough to retire it. LCOGT(1, 20200203, clouded out, 20200212 pending). Maybe on TIC146129313 (which is also cluster member, and is ~5 arcsec separated neighbor to NE). HJ in Vela OB2 pop6 (20Myr, CG19). Have S7 and S8 LC. If Teff=6670K, it’s plausible that it should not show rotation period (exactly the transition region in eg. Curtis 2019 fig 4). Recon spectrrum gives 2020-01-27T06-22-18.9 2458875.78853 RV -96.606 0.714 Teff 6435 logg 4.28 feh 0.44 vsini 16.0. vsini of 16km/s for a 6400K dwarf (Rstar=1.3 or 1.4) is uncomfortably low; it drives Prot to like 4 or 5 days, instead of the 2 or 3 where it is expected. I think holding off for phot followup is the right approach here.  Phot followup yields: V-shaped transit signal is present, due to TIC146129313 rather than 146129309... need to update this entry correspondingly!! Howell found (Mar 2020) no Zorro companions.

name: kc19group_264
comment: Cand HJ; hot star; Theia 264 (90 Myr claimed; KC19; existence questionable). 20200219 Phil Evans 1 on-target and VPC in i-band. Boosted to TOI postCDIPS.

name: LCC
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP0 (V=16.5, K=10.4). Ideal for TripleSpec. 1 veloce recon spectrum acquired to check for Li (wavelength calibration pending).
pending_photometry_observations: PP1. It’s grazing. Get zs and gs with 1meter. -- observable <20201130. Partials attempted, also none in 20B.
comment: Cand super-Neptune; PMS M dwarf (Zari+18, rotn period). This one seems real. Phil Evans observed a full on 20200311 in Ic, seems on target. Boost to VPC. LCOGT(2, 20200207, 20200208 did not reduce well). Don Radford observed a full on 20200319 in I and detected a ~16 minute early ~10 ppt V-shaped event in a 4.4" uncontaminated target aperture. Again, seems good. 20200320 Phil Evans observed a full in clear band, remains VPC. Multisector. S12+S13. Seems good in both. Given transit duration, V-shape is expected.  NB given M dwarf, rotn period is helpful, but does not age-date.  This system is closer than trappist-1. Maybe shows extra dips (multiplanet) too.  Note: boosted to be a TOI post-CDIPS.  Aaron Rizzuto then wrote to note that it is a candidate member of Sco Cen (LCC, specifically). Likely younger than 20 Myr.  Goldman+2018 says so;  Marton+2016 thought it was a "Class III" YSO based on the WISE data.  Veloce check for Li pending (for M0 or M1V PMS dwarf, expect to probably see it). Worth acquiring zs and gz band phot, perhaps with 2 meter.  To be clear though: QLP report shows it is GRAZING (b=0.9-1.1), so this is an annoying object, and probably a BEB. Howell found (Mar 2020) no Zorro companions.

name: Johansson_1
comment: Probable EB. Cand HJ in "Johansson 1" (maybe nonexistent, but stars more coeval than nbhd).

name: ASCC 24
comment: Candidate 30 Myr massive star with giant planet. Kinematics and phot plausible with cluster membership, but ASCC 24 is sparse, and K13 labels a MG.  However CG18 does not recover -- raises suspicions about the existence of the group itself.  Photometry would be surprisingly quiet for a 30 Myr star.  Need RV to check for consistency with Kharchenko+13 RV. Otherwise, further analysis of the group's existence is needed.

name: Bochum 5
comment: Phase modulation strongly suggests short-period eccentric EB.

name: Basel_11A
comment: Low SNR & crowded. Needs ground-based transits to confirm presence of signal, and location. Purported 2% signal, 50 Myr-old.

name: NGC_2548,NGC_2548,NGC2548
comment: Good SNR signal, V-shaped. SG2 lists: "V-shaped; Large planet; but could be close to 2 R_Jup. WASP follow-up shows this is a low-mass EB." CG18 P_memb = 100%, thuogh the LAMOST RV suggests otherwise (at low significance?). In M48, 400 Myr. Worth including in any homogeneous paper.

name: FSR_1077
comment: Tdur somewhat long, but good signal. CG18 doesn't recover FSR 1077 cluster (but it's an IR cluster). Froebrich+07 called it a "probable" cluster, rather than a "possible" one. However they raise a quality flag indicating that the contrast of the central to background star density is low. So basically: the cluster's existence still needs to be confirmed (or refuted) thru joint DR2 5dims + 2MASS photometry. Because based on optical data alone, its existence is not clear. Nbhd analysis shows Gaia PM and parallax don't cohere into any meaningful clump. This "cluster" is probably not real.

name: ASCC 35
comment: Outskirts of ASCC 35. Good signal (+weak spot modulation). CG18 didn't recover cluster, and no cluster RV available -> priority 1 instead of 0. Nbhd analysis shows: this cluster is just not at all apparent. Probably doesn't exist. (Downgraded furhter).

name: Platais 6
comment: Phase modulation-> EB.

name: Berkeley_28
comment: Cand young (~50 Myr) massive star w/ giant planet. Somewhat V-shaped. Proper motions suggest members in cluster outskirts. RV needed to confirm 6d position+velocity agree with cluster association. NB. strong spot modulation supports youth. Nbhd analysis shows PMs are just WAY OFF.

name: Collinder 70,--,Collinder 70,--
comment: Hot star, cluster outskirts, pulsation variability. Star is HD 37173, Houk+1999 classified as B6 II, with what they reported as a high-quality spectrum --> expected Rstar is 6Rsun. Dip is 0.5%. If SpType is correct, almost certainly stellar.

name: Collinder 70
comment: Good signal, questionable parallax (i.e. maybe not cluster member). Star is also not photometrically active enough for how young it's supposed to be. Possible OOT ellipsoidal phase variation. Only RV for cluster membership -- stellar mass EBs to be ruled out after. Nbhd analysis shows definitely not member (but that Collinder 70 is obviously real).

name: NGC_2516
comment: TLS double period. P~4 day HJ cand in NGC 2516. Multiple sector data available -> would benefit from analysis. Nbhd analysis shows that parallax is a bit small. Proper motions seem quite off. RV to confirm it's in the cluster would be needed... or to confirm youth. Weak membership. CHIRON (1, Zhou) shows double-peaked CCF, no signs of Li.

name: Gulliver_36
comment: Poss off-target, but WCS suspect (pg6) --> would need to be reanalyzed in a separate pipeline run.
Candidate PMS M-dwarf + HJ/BD/M dwarf.  BLS 2x period shows better OOT phase-modulation fit --> likely EB.

name: Collinder 132
comment: Raw LC OOT variations suspect --> either an EB, or a WASP-18 like HJ.  Parallax and photometry fine for cluster membership, but the proper motion is bad, indicating likely field contami--t. --theless, v nice signal. One or two RVs needed to confirm not cluster member. Don't follow for mass measurement until clarified. Nbhd analysis shows (a) the CG18 cluster members seem wrong.  The clump in proper motion space for Collinder 132 is different from where the members are. (b) From the PMs star is no way in either of the clumps. So it’s a HJ/EB around a field star. NB Quinn uploaded 1 spectroscopy observation. high vsini, line profiles look good. 2020-01-05T07-09-44.6 2458853.81452 RV -21.056 0.229 Teff 6329 logg 4.2 feh -0.1 vsini 30.1

name: NGC_2354
comment: Cand HJ in NGC 2354, a 300 Myr cluster. Note = HATS554-051.  Joel Hartman writes: "We have two egresses from the LCOGT 1m network, and an ingress observed by CHAT. We have 9 FEROS observations and 6 HARPS observations that show a fair amount of scatter, and do not phase up with the photometric ephemeris (we get a best-fit orbit of K = 100 +- 40 m/s). Probably this is due to the rapid rotation of the star. We have this marked as being in need of photometric follow-up in another band-pass, photometric follow-up covering a secondary eclipse, and blend analysis." TESS data enables all.  For cluster membership, Kharchenko gives Ps|Pkin|PJKs|PJH as  1|80.44|73.95|94.64.  The ~30-31km/s from the WiFeS/HARPS/FEROS RVs seem pretty consistent with the star being a cluster member.  Metallicity is also fine.  NB only 1 sector of TESS data available.  This is probably ready to publish, after a detailed blend analysis. However, a detailed manual analysis of the stars in the neighborhood by LGB showed that the parallax and proper motions are inconsistent with cluster membership -- the star is a foreground star.  In addition, the MS turnoff of the cluster is like ~2Msun, while this star is ~1.4Msun. Shy of any spectroscopic indications of stellar youth (e.g., Li? Halpha?), the cluster membership claim should be treated with heavy skepticism.

name: Octans
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP2. (V=9.2). Being led by Tofflemire. Rp=3.2Re and Mann discovered. What is vsini from Quinn’s 20191205 spectrum? He flagged as “not appropriate for PRVs”
comment: TOI 1098 in Octans, identified by Andrew Mann. Annoyingly close to pole. P=10d, Rp=3.5Re, shallow. Rotn period good. Teff=6150K, T=8.7 (bright!). S12+13. Good RV target. Spitzer transit acquired (Newton), not much need for any phot with LCO. Prot of ~3 day or shorter. Spot amplitude ~0.8% (2 min SPOC report from Burke on ExoFOP-TESS). Quinn has taken 1 CHIRON spectrum 20191205. Not a CDIPS target star v0.4 … what is Mann’s proof of membership? Tofflemire leading the charge on this one.

name: kc19group_64,--,kc19group_64,--
pending_photometry_observations: PP0, get zs. -- observable <20201130. Partials attempted.
comment: TOI 1227 in Eps Cha, identified by Andrew Mann. P=27d, Rp=16Re, deep (M dwarf, V=17, T=13.8). S11+12, only 2 dips seen. Need phot followup. Mann leans towards “not planet” b/c of odd SOAR transit. Collins (SG1) got IBE, looks plausible. It’s in Kounkel’s group 64, and is also labelled PMS M dwarf from Zari.

name: ASCC_127,RSG_7,--,ASCC_127,RSG_7,--
pending_photometry_observations: PP0, get gp (maybe x2). 8 OIBEO sched thru 20200921
comment: TOI 1497 in RSG_7 (200Myr), identified by Jerome de Leon. Rp=4Re, P=0.82d USP around V=10 hot star. 0.5mmag transits, but maybe worth clearing field of NEBs for validation. TRES (1, Bieryla) shows Vrot~120km/s, no chance at mass measurement. Doppler tomography still possible? Nbhd plot shows membership looks good. QLP report shows not grazing (b=0.10 thru 0.70).

name: ScoCen
comment: TIC 166527623 = HIP 67522 in Sco Cen.  Rizzuto+2020 THYME2 validated, b near 0. Claimed  HJ; but no mass. No RM yet either. CDIPS + TOI totally missed this one.  (T=9.2! So easy followup). Spitzer transit (Newton) acquired.  Params from paper. Note a single-transit was reported too. Use the ephemeris to follow it up.

name: young_field
comment: Teff = 4500K, Rp=2.5Re, Porb=11d, "quiet" mid K dwarf.  No Li.  Whopping Ca HK, at the level that implies <500 Myr almost certainly.  (Err. How many others have such Ca HK? Would be nice to automate!) Prot = 8 days, strong signal.  Keck AO done and looks great.  SG1 seems to have lost the ephemeris. (And as of Feb 2020 it's currently behind the sun AFAIK. 1 mmag transit, so not surprising!).  SG2 shows that Veloce team has gotten 17 shots. Surprising, given Prot and Porb so close. I guess after S1 of EM1, with extra transits we might stand a chance. (This is literally July 2020, which is quite soon. Two years sure passes quick!).

name: cg19velaOB2_pop7,N/A
pending_spectroscopic_observations: SP1. NRES-Johnson acquired a recon spectrum.
pending_photometry_observations: [todo]PP0, get ip. [20B visible]. Large ephem unc. 6 sched events <20201130.
comment: PC. T=9, Rp=4.6, P=3.5, Teff 8500K. From default neighborhood look, somewhat evolved A star. PmRA is a bit off of the obvious cluster.

name: Gulliver_60
comment: KC19, needs check. (Interesting cluster). FIES (Buchave) showed vrot 200km/s. Bp-Rp=0 would imply Teff 9000K, not 13000. 2mmag dip. Would make it A2V, Rstar = 2-3Rsun depending on Teff. 0.2% would imply Rp~=Rjup. Worth DT, in that case! Nbhd analysis shows star is on outskirts of cluster. It’s not a CG18 member dude. Membership claim seems likely to be spurious. (just based on how far off it is in ra/dec space, and in the HR diagram).

name: RSG_5,--,RSG_5,--
comment: 200km/s. T=8, Rp=4.4, P=2.3d. Membership from nbhd plot seems questionable. Weird 3-part string. Off in HR diagram too (too bright). PMs and plx seem fine-enough. Just might be a random A-star, and not a CM.

name: kc19group_597
comment: Rp 6.0, P=4.6, K9V/M0V. d=160pc, bright for M dwarf. No Prot, when there should be one. So it’s probably bad. Cluster existence highly dubious, with very few members, no obvious kinematic excess.

Rp 5.0, P=7.88, ZariPMS. 3 dips including eleanor LC (2 in CDIPS). 120pc. Giving up on it because closer inspection did not reveal correct periodicity. Checked w Chelsea Huang, and the QLP products also were suggestive but not conclusive, at low SNR. Wait for Ext Mission.

name: NGC_5617
comment: EB or Warm Jup, NGC 5617 (170Myr, CG18). If dwarf, Teff would be 6500K based on gaia colors. GaiaHRD supports star being dwarf. Planet size here is wrong, it would really be around 1.5Rjup. But Is a 6.5hr transit durn possible? Answer: no, the transit duration is too long. Would imply rhostar = 0.12rhosun, while in reality for a F5V dwarf (which the HRD implies) rhostar=0.43rhosun. Factor of 3-4x wrong. Probably EB. Unless EM1 provides a miracle.

name: NGC_5925
comment: Likely EB, NGC 5925 (180Myr, CG18). Star properties unclear, but star is hot.

name: Alessi_8,Alessi_8
comment: Likely EB, Alessi 8 (CG18, 120Myr). Prot 6d; dubious bc Teff 6500K.

name: Collinder_307
pending_photometry_observations: [todo]PP0, get -ip-,-gp-,[zs]. Waiting for zs until reduc.
comment: Crowded. HJ or EB. Collinder 307 (CG18, 30Myr). pmDec off. Secondary eclipse seems like its present. Probably young EB.  1 ip and 2 gp obtained, reduc pending.

name: NGC_6193
comment: 10 Myr EB or HJ. PMS K dwarf host (NGC 6193, CG18). LCOGT shows there's an EB 120 arcseconds away... is it really blended? Answer from second LCOGT LC: probably, yes. Neighbor is W UMa EB, and there’s strong filter dependence.

pending_photometry_observations: PP0, get [zs],gp,ip. 1 OIBE at <20201130, and a few partials. -- executed.
comment: PMS K dwarf HJ (Zari+18). Prot 2d, RotAmp 8%. Good target. We got RM with Veloce on 20200823, which may have turned out ok -- see the chain with Chris Tinney.
Likely EB. PMS (Zari+18), Teff 5000K, Prot 5d, ampltiude 2%.

comment: Hot Jup. PMS M dwarf (Zari+18), Prot 2d?, Tdur a bit long.absHot

comment: superNept. PMS M dwarf (Zari+18). Prot  0.8d, RotAmp 5%. 3 ip/zs/gp reductions showed a dip in zs, ip/gp unclear. Tried again in ip, reduction pending.

name: kc19group_1502
comment: Host is a subgiant field star.

name: kc19group_1098
comment: HATS-47. Theia 1098 (KC19); cluster existence dubious.

name: IC_2602,IC_2602,IC2602
comment: PATHOS-31: IC2602 Rp=4Re NON-GRAZING candidate. High quality.

name: fieldyoung
comment: TOI-251: Zhou+20 shows <200 Myr + validated. Rp=2.7, P=5d.

name: fieldyoung

name: NGC_2422,--,NGC_2422,--
comment: SP2, PP1. Star is far from cluster core but could be part of fuzz-like population. Check Prot-Teff of the fuzz to see if the Kounkel members are real. FIES(1) shows Vrot=160km/s. Age of NGC 2422 is pretty low. Roughly 100 Myr. Gamma velocity would be interesting. If it is 35km/s would help the membership. Buchave et al sent me the spectrum, suggests cross-correlating against an appropriate template (ThAr calibration was done for the wvlen soln).  Clearly hard to derive a velocity. Let it sit, for a while, until EM1 improves ephemeris for free.

ABDor MG member (50 Myr). Identified by George Zhou. Not yet a TOI. 500 or 600 ppm depth. V=8.3, perhaps good for RM. Has a single archival UVES observation. The spectrum is of very high SNR, shows significant Li absorption, and a vsini of 30 km/s.

comment: Found by Ben Montet & Elsa. 15 Myr PC with extra dips (disintegrating? unclear). In LCC / Upper Sco.

George Zhou found. V=9.95 K-dwarf observed in Sectors 1 and 28. The search showed up two planets around this relatively active star: at 7.6-day period / 1.9 Rearth and a 14.2 day / 2.4 Rearth.  This star is less likely to be extremely young, with a rotation period of ~6 days, it will need reconnaissance observations from CHIRON to check for activity and Li before being placed in the interesting category. George notes it has two HARPS observations from 2013. The spectra show a small amount of Li absorption, likely suggesting this star is not much younger than Praesepe. The RVs do not differ by more than 20m/s, with a vsini of 7km/s. I will go ahead with further observations for this target.

George Zhou found. V=12.41 late K / early-M dwarf in sector-28 with a 1.3d period hot Neptune at Rp=4Re. It is high in the HRD, potentially implying a photometric binary, or perhaps that it is on the PMS. Has archival UVES (ESO) spectrum. No sign of SB2, exhibits no Li absorption, but shows significant p-cygni structure in H-alpha, and a very complicated emission profile in Ca HK. The lack of Li is OK, given the speed of Li depletion in low mass stars. George suggests to keep on going with this target too.
